## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("List all items from the API.")]
    public async Task<string> ListItems(
        [Description("Maximum number of items to return")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Listing up to {Limit} items", limit);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/api/items?limit={limit}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a single item by its unique identifier.")]
    public async Task<string> GetItem(
        [Description("The unique item ID")] string id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching item {Id}", id);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/api/items/{id}", cancellationToken);
        if (!response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
            return $"Error: {response.StatusCode}";
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(Destructive = false, ReadOnly = false),
     Description("Create a new item with the given name and description.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateItem(
        [Description("Name for the new item")] string name,
        [Description("Optional description")] string? description = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, description });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/api/items", content, cancellationToken);
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|-------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor; resolved once per tool class instance |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | Services as method params alongside user-facing params |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `IHttpClientFactory`, etc.) plus special types (`CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<T>`) are **injected automatically** and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema sent to the LLM. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

In the example above, `ApiTools` uses **constructor injection** — `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected via the primary constructor. The `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(...)` call in `Program.cs` registers a typed `HttpClient` that the SDK resolves when it instantiates `ApiTools`.

**Checklist:**
- Every tool class → `[McpServerToolType]`
- Every tool method → `[McpServerTool]` + `[Description]`
- Every user-facing parameter → `[Description]`
- Logging → stderr only (stdout = protocol wire)
